1 (2) conducts or procures another to conduct visual surveillance of an
2 individual to protect property or public safety or prevent crime; or
3 (3) conducts visual surveillance and:
4 (i) holds a license issued under Title 13 or Title 19 of the Business
5 Occupations and Professions Article; and
6 (ii) is acting within the scope of the person’s occupation.
7 (c) A person may not with prurient intent conduct or procure another to conduct
8 visual surveillance of:
9 (1) an individual in a private place without the consent of that individual;
10 or
11 (2) the private area of an individual by use of a camera without the consent
12 of the individual under circumstances in which a reasonable person would believe that the
13 private area of the individual would not be visible to the public, regardless of whether the
14 individual is in a public or private place.
15 (d) A person who violates this section is guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction
16 is subject to imprisonment not exceeding 1 year or a fine not exceeding $2,500 or both.
17 (e) (1) An individual who was under visual surveillance in violation of this
18 section has a civil cause of action against any person who conducted or procured another to
19 conduct the visual surveillance.
20 (2) In an action under this subsection, the court may award actual damages
21 and reasonable attorney’s fees.
22 (f) This section does not affect any legal or equitable right or remedy otherwise
23 provided by law.
24 (g) This section does not affect the application of § 3–901 of this subtitle.
25 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
26 October 1, 2025.

